The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Thursday, January 22, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, Jan. 21: The government is unlikley to advance the exim policy in the face of the Lok Sabha elections, but may come out with some procedural changes to provide relief to exporters ahead of Parliament session beginning on January 29 to pass vote on account. It now appears that the exim policy would be left to the new government for paucity of time, official sources said.																								 Mumbai, Jan. 21: GTL Ltd, in its board meeting on January 22, will consider a proposal to set up a 100 per cent subsidiary to cater to Motorola Indias cellular infrastructure projects exclusively and give the latter a right to acquire a shareholding of up to 49 per cent in this subsidiary.																								 Mumbai, Jan. 21: The Securities and Exchange Board of India today widened the scope of its informal guidance scheme guidelines to provide such advice to mutual funds and companies which plan to list securities on the exchanges and also companies planning acquisition.																								 Chennai, Jan. 21: UTI Mutual Fund (UTI MF) and Indian Bank today entered into a strategic tie-up under which the entire bouquet of UTI MFs schemes would be made available in the banks selected branches.																								 Bangalore, Jan. 21: iGate Global Solutions today said it planned to acquire Symphoni Interactive, a US-based financial consulting firm, from its parent iGate Corporation in the next 60 to 90 days.
